  "articleSummary": "The article argues that PostgreSQL's native search tools—**full-text search (tsvector/GIN)**, **trigrams (pg_trgm)**, and **exact-match indexes**—should be used in combination rather than isolation to optimize search functionality. It emphasizes matching tools to query requirements: full-text search for lexical analysis (e.g., articles), trigrams for fuzzy matching (e.g., typos, autocompletion), and exact-match indexes for binary matches (e.g., IDs, emails). The core thesis is that teams often overcomplicate search by relying on a single tool or external services, when layering Postgres-native options reduces complexity and cost. The tone is analytical and tutorial, framed around a visual \"tool map\" that categorizes use cases by input type and intent. Intended for developers and database engineers seeking to implement efficient, scalable search in PostgreSQL.",
